          <div class="card">
            <p>Adolescent well-being issues in Qatar have affected thousands of lives, with data showing a significant portion of youth face physical, mental, and social health challenges, placing this issue at the heart of national concern [1][2][3][4].</p>
            <h4>Prevalence and Direct Impact</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Up to half of Qatari adolescents report engaging in risky or unhealthy behaviors; over 34% of boys under 20 are overweightâ€”the highest regional rate [4][1].</li>
              <li>One in five people in Qatar will experience a mental illness at some point, with adolescents heavily represented [3].</li>
              <li>Among secondary school students (13â€“15 years), nearly 44% have engaged in unlicensed driving, 38% in physical fights, 31% have not worn seatbelts, and 22% have smoked cigarettes [4].</li>
              <li>The prevalence of iron deficiency among adolescents reached 26.4%, indicating tens of thousands affected nationwide [2].</li>
            </ul>
            <h4>Mental Health and Social Effects</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Depression is the most common mental health issue among young adults, with 75% of surveyed adolescents identifying it as a serious concern [5][4].</li>
              <li>Most families report irritability, nervousness, and hostile behavior among adolescents seeking help at clinics [6].</li>
            </ul>
            <h4>Systemic Consequences</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>These challenges lead to lower educational achievement, higher unemployment, and greater risk of lifelong health problems, increasing the burden on society [7][8].</li>
              <li>Tens of thousands of adolescents face serious well-being concerns affecting daily life and future prospects [2][3][4].</li>
            </ul>
            <p>These statistics underscore the urgency of addressing adolescent well-being as a national concern [1][3][2][4].</p>
          </div>
